\begin_layout Standard
The justification for many of the upcoming claims relies heavily on induction
 (see axiom 5 of crumpet 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "dig:peano-axioms"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "axiom:induction"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The principle behind induction is to show that (i) the claim is actually
 true for some particular integer, and (ii) if the claim is true for some
 integer at least as large, then it is also true for the next integer.
 This way, part (i) establishes the claim for a particular integer, say
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Then part (ii) establishes the claim for the next integer, 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1$
\end_inset

.
 Part (i) also establishes the claim for the next integer, 
\begin_inset Formula $k+2$
\end_inset

.
 Applying part (i) again establishes the claim for the next integer, 
\begin_inset Formula $k+3$
\end_inset

, and so on, part (i) establishing the claim for all integers greater than
 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Induction is often the most practical way to show that a statement is true
 for all integers and is particularly useful in proving claims about matrices
 of size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 (for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

).
 Proofs of this nature will be shown, but this is not a course on proof
 technique, so it is up to you or your instructor to decide how deeply you
 need to understand these proofs.
 Even if you are not prepared for full comprehension or writing your own
 induction proofs, reading them is a good way to get a feel for the technique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An 
\series bold
upper triangular matrix
\series default
 is one in which all entries below the main diagonal are zero, and a 
\series bold
lower triangular matrix
\series default
 is one in which all entries above the main diagonal are zero.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $\star$
\end_inset

 to represent any number (as in the notation of section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Echelon-Forms"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), a square upper triangular matrix looks like
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccccc}
\star & \star & \star & \star & \cdots & \star\\
0 & \star & \star & \star & \cdots & \star\\
0 & 0 & \star & \star & \cdots & \star\\
0 & 0 & 0 & \star & \cdots & \star\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \star\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 0 & \cdots & \star
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and a square lower triangular matrix looks like 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccccc}
\star & 0 & 0 & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
\star & \star & 0 & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
\star & \star & \star & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
\star & \star & \star & \star & \cdots & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & 0\\
\star & \star & \star & \star & \cdots & \star
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

All the nonzero entries are above or on the main diagonal (the upper triangle)
 for an upper triangular matrix, and all the nonzero entries are below or
 on the main diagonal (the lower triangle) for a lower triangular matrix.
 The determinant of a lower triangular matrix is the product of the entrieson
 its diagonal.
 Now is a good time to work out a couple examples on your own and think
 about why this is true in general.
 We will prove it by induction, but the proof may not resonate with you
 the way your own thoughts about it will.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim*
If 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a lower triangular 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det L=L_{1,1}L_{2,2}\cdots L_{n,n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
If 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $1\times1$
\end_inset

 matrix, it is upper triangular and 
\begin_inset Formula $\det L=\det\left(\left[L_{1,1}\right]\right)=L_{1,1}$
\end_inset

.
 This establishes part (i) of the proof.
 The claim is true for the particular value 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

.
 Now we assume that the claim is true for some (arbitrary) value 
\begin_inset Formula $n=k$
\end_inset

 greater than or equal to one.
 That is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a lower triangular 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times k$
\end_inset

 matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det L=L_{1,1}L_{2,2}\cdots L_{k,k}$
\end_inset

.
 To complete the proof, we must use this information to prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $(k+1)\times(k+1)$
\end_inset

 matrix, the next integer size up, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det L=L_{1,1}L_{2,2}\cdots L_{k+1,k+1}$
\end_inset

, so suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $(k+1)\times(k+1)$
\end_inset

 matrix.
 By definition,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\det L=(-1)^{1+1}L_{1,1}\det L_{\backslash1,1}+(-1)^{1+2}L_{1,2}\det L_{\backslash1,2}\cdots+(-1)^{1+3}L_{1,3}\det L_{\backslash1,3}\label{eq:det-lower-triangular-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is lower triangular, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1,j}=0$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $j>1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, all the terms of the determinant are zero except the first one.
 That is, the determinant simplifies to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\det L=L_{1,1}\det L_{\backslash1,1}.\label{eq:det-lower-triangular-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

But 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{\backslash1,1}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times k$
\end_inset

 matrix, so its determinant is the product of the entries on its diagonal
 (this is our inductive hypothesis).
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\det L_{\backslash1,1}=L_{2,2}L_{3,3}\cdots L_{k+1,k+1}$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting this expression into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:det-lower-triangular-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\det L=L_{1,1}L_{2,2}L_{3,3}\cdots L_{k+1,k+1}$
\end_inset

, and the proof is complete.
\end_layout

