\begin_layout Claim*
If 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an upper triangular 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det U=U_{1,1}U_{2,2}\cdots U_{n,n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
If 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $1\times1$
\end_inset

 matrix, it is upper triangular and 
\begin_inset Formula $\det\left(\left[U_{1,1}\right]\right)=U_{1,1}$
\end_inset

.
 This establishes part (i) of the proof.
 The claim is true for the particular value 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

.
 Now we assume that the claim is true for some (arbitrary) value 
\begin_inset Formula $n=k$
\end_inset

 greater than or equal to one.
 That is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an upper triangular 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times k$
\end_inset

 matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det U=U_{1,1}U_{2,2}\cdots U_{k,k}$
\end_inset

.
 To complete the proof, we must use this information to prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $(k+1)\times(k+1)$
\end_inset

 matrix then 
\begin_inset Formula $\det U=U_{1,1}U_{2,2}\cdots U_{k+1,k+1}$
\end_inset

, so suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $(k+1)\times(k+1)$
\end_inset

 matrix.
 By definition,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det U=(-1)^{1+1}U_{1,1}\det U_{\backslash1,1}+(-1)^{1+2}U_{1,2}\det U_{\backslash1,2}\cdots+(-1)^{1+3}U_{1,3}\det U_{\backslash1,3}
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{\backslash1,j}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times k$
\end_inset

 matrix, its determinant is the product of the entries on its diagonal (this
 is our inductive hypothesis).
 Since there is a zero on the diagonal whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $j>1$
\end_inset

, all terms except the first are zero.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\det U=(-1)^{1+1}U_{1,1}\det U_{\backslash1,1}$
\end_inset

.
 Again using the inductive hypothesis, 
\begin_inset Formula $\det U_{\backslash1,1}$
\end_inset

 is the product of the entries on its main diagonal, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2,2}U_{3,3}\cdots U_{k+1,k+1}$
\end_inset

.
 Putting this observation together with 
\begin_inset Formula $\det U=(-1)^{1+1}U_{1,1}\det U_{\backslash1,1}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\det U=U_{1,1}U_{2,2}U_{3,3}\cdots U_{k+1,k+1}$
\end_inset

, and the proof is complete.
\end_layout

